urrent version is' b'available via anonymous ftp from host ftp.ee.lbl.gov (currently at' b'address file tcpdump.tar.z (a compressed unix tar' b"file). this program is subject to the 'standard' berkeley network" b'software copyright.' b'' b'_____' b'<4.2 how can i learn about or use cryptography?' b'' b'a general introduction to mostly theoretical cryptographic issues,' b'especially those frequently discussed in sci.crypt, is available' b'in faq form:' b'' b' compiled by:' b'' b'nist (u.s. national institute for standards and technology)' b'publishes an introductory paper on cryptography, special' b"publication ``public-key cryptograhy'' by james nechvatal" b'(april available via anonymous ftp from' b'csrc.ncsl.nist.gov file pub/nistpubs/800-2.txt.' b'also via available anonymous ftp from wimsey.bc.ca as crypt.txt.z' b'in the crypto directory. covers technical mathematical aspects' b'of encryption such as number theory.' b'' b'more general information can be found in a faq by paul fahn of rsa' b'labortories via anonymous ftp from rsa.com in /pub/faq.ps.z. see' b"the `readme' file for information on the `tex' version. also" b'available as hardcopy for from rsa laboratories, marine' b'parkway, redwood city, ca send questions to' b'' b"phil zimmerman's pgp (pretty good privacy) public-domain package" b'for public key encryption is available at numerous sites, and is' b'in widespread use over the internet for general unix-based file' b'encryption (including email). consult the archie ftp database.' b'also see the newsgroup alt.security.pgp. mailing list requests' b'' b'from the ripem faq by marc vanheyningen' b'' b' ripem is a program which performs privacy enhanced mail (pem)' b' using the cryptographic techniques of rsa and des. it allows' b' your electronic mail to have the properties of authentication' b' (i.e. who sent it can be confirmed) and privacy (i.e. nobody can' b' read it except the intended recipient.)' b'' b' ripem was written primarily by mark riordan' b' except for the rsa routines, which are a library called rsaref' b' licensed from rsa data security inc.' b'' b' ripem is available via anonymous ftp to citizens and permanent' b' residents in the u.s. from rsa.com; cd to rsaref/ and read the' b' readme file for info.' b'' b" ripem, as well as some other crypt stuff, has its `home site' on" b' rpub.cl.msu.edu, which is open to non-anonymous ftp for users in' b' the u.s. and canada who are citizens or permanent residents. to' b' find out how to obtain access, ftp there, cd to pub/crypt/, and' b' read the file getting_access.' b'' b'note: cryptography is generally not well integrated into email yet' b'and some system proficiency is required by users to utilize it.' b'' b'_____' b'<4.3 what is the cypherpunks mailing list?' b'' b'dedicated to ``discussion about technological defenses for privacy' b"in the digital domain.'' send email to" b'list. from the charter:' b'' b' the most important means to the defense of privacy is encryption.' b' to encrypt is to indicate the desire for privacy. but to encrypt' b' with weak cryptography is to indicate not too much desire for' b' privacy. cypherpunks hope that all people desiring privacy will' b' learn how best to defend it.' b'' b'_____' b'<4.4 what are some privacy-related newsgroups? faqs?' b'' b'newsgroups' b'==========' b'' b'alt.comp.acad-freedom.news' b'alt.comp.acad-freedom.talk' b'--------------------------' b'moderated and unmoderated issues related to academic freedom and' b'privacy at universities. documented examples of violated' b"privacy in e.g. email. documented examples of `censorship' as" b'in e.g. limiting usenet groups local availability.' b'' b'alt.cyberpunks' b'--------------' b'virtual reality, (science) fiction by william gibson and bruce' b'sterling, cyberpunk in the mainstream.' b'' b'alt.hackers' b'-----------' b'usenet network news transfer protocol (nntp) posting mechanisms,' b"simple mail transfer protocol (smtp), `obligatory hack' reports." b'' b