ews transfer protocol' b'rfc-1036: standard for interchange of network news messages' b'rfc-1208: glossary of networking terms' b"rfc-1207: answers to ``experienced internet user'' questions" b"rfc-1206: answers to ``new internet user'' questions" b'rfc-1355: privacy issues in network information center databases' b'' b'' b"rfc-1177 is ``fyi: answers to commonly asked ``new internet user''" b'questions, and includes: basic terminology on the internet (tcp/ip,' b'smtp, ftp), internet organizations such as iab (internet' b'activities board) and ietf (internet enbgineering task force), and' b'a glossary of terms. also from ftp.eff.org:' b'/pub/internet-info/internet.q.' b'' b' rfcs can be obtained via ftp from nic.ddn.mil, with the pathname' b" rfc:rfcnnnn.txt or rfc:rfcnnnn.ps (where `nnnn' refers to the" b" number of the rfc). login with ftp, username `anonymous' and" b" password `guest'. the nic also provides an automatic mail" b' service for those sites which cannot use ftp. address the' b'' b' rfcs can also be obtained via ftp from nis.nsf.net. using ftp,' b" login with username `anonymous' and password `guest'; then" b" connect to the rfc directory (`cd rfc'). the file name is of the" b" form rfcnnnn.txt-1 (where `nnnn' refers to the number of the" b' rfc). the nis also provides an automatic mail service for those' b' sites which cannot use ftp. address the request to' b' blank. the first line of the text of the message must be `send' b" rfcnnnn.txt-1', where nnnn is replaced by the rfc number." b'' b'_____' b'<4.7 how can i run an anonymous remailer?' b'' b'cypherpunk remailer source is at soda.berkeley.edu in the' b"/pub/cypherpunks directory. it's written in perl, and is" b'relatively easy to install (no administrative rights are required).' b'modifications. also, most remailer operators mentioned above are' b'amenable to discussing features, problems, and helping new sites' b'become operational. address all points in the section' b"``responsibities of anonymous use'' in this document prior to" b'advertising your service. you should be committed to the long-term' b'stability of the site and avoid running one surreptitiously.' b'' b'_____' b'<4.8 what are references on privacy in email?' b'' b'' b"brown, bob. ``ema urges users to adopt policy on e-mail privacy.''" b'network world (oct b'' b"bairstow, jeffrey. ``who reads your electronic mail?'' electronic" b'business (june b'' b"``electronic envelopes the uncertainty of keeping e-mail private''" b'scientific american, february b'' b'ftp.eff.org' b'===========' b'' b'/pub/eff/papers/email_privacy' b'---' b'article on the rights of email privacy. by ruel t. hernandez.' b'' b'/pub/academic/law/privacy.email' b'---' b"``computer electronic mail and privacy'', an edited version of a" b'law school seminar paper by ruel t. hernadez.' b'' b'/pub/eff/papers/email-privacy-biblio-2' b'---' b'compilation of bibliography on e-mail and its privacy issues (part' b'2 of the work). compiled by stacy b. veeder b'' b'/pub/eff/papers/email-privacy-research' b'---' b'the author at digital research tried to formalize their employee' b'privacy policy on e-mail. the casesightings are divided into two' b'groups: us constitutional law, and california law.' b'' b'/pub/eff/papers/company-email' b'---' b'formulating a company policy on access to and disclosure of' b'electronic mail on company computer systems by david r. johnson' b'and john podesta for the electronic mail assocation' b'' b'/pub/cud/alcor' b'---' b'information on alcor co., an e-mail privacy suit.' b'' b'/pub/academic/law/privacy.email' b'---' b'email privacy search at berkeley.' b'' b'_____' b'<4.9 what are some email, usenet, and internet use policies?' b'' b'the computer policy and critiques archive is a collection of the' b'computer policies of many schools and networks, run by the' b'computers and academic freedom group on the electronic frontier' b'foundation ftp site. the collection also includes critiques of some' b'of the policies.' b'' b' if you have gopher, the archive is browsable with the command:' b' gopher -p academic/policies gopher.eff.org' b'' b' the archive is also accessible via anonymous ftp and email. ftp' b' to ftp.eff.org it is in directory' b" `pub/academic/policies'. for email access, send email to" b'' b' send acad-freedom/policies <filenames' b'' b' where <filenames is a list of the files that you want. file' b' readme is a detailed description of the items in the directory.' b'' b' for more information, to make contributions, or to report typos' b' contains additional policies (but not critiques).' b'' b'' b'ftp.eff.org' b'===========' b'' b'/pub/cud/networks' b'---' b'acceptable use policies for various networks, including compuserve' b"(file `compuserve'), nsfnet (file `nsfnet') with information on" b'research and commercial uses. see /pub/cud/networks/index.' b'' b'/pub/cud/networks/email' b'---' b'policies from various sysadmins about how they handle the issue of' b'email privacy, control, and abuse, compiled by t. hooper' b'' b'/pub/cud/schools/' b'---' b'computer use policies of a number of schools. see schools/index' b'for a full list and description.' b'' b'' b'commentary' b'==========' b'' b'/pub/academic/faq/policy.best' b'---' b'opinions on the best academic computer policies.' b'' b'' b'/pub/academic/faq/email.policies' b'---' b'do any universities treat email and computer files as private?' b'' b'/pub/academic/faq/netnews.writing' b'---' b'policies on what users write on usenet.' b'' b'/pub/academic/faq/netnews.reading' b'---' b'policies on what users read on usenet: should my university remove' b'(or restrict) netnews newsgroups because some people find them' b'offensive?' b'' b'/pub/academic/faq/policy' b'---' b"what guidance is there for creating or evaluating a university's" b'academic computer policy?' b'' b'______' b"<4.10 what is the mit ``crosslink'' anonymous message tv program?" b'' b' crosslink is an anonymous message system run on mit student' b' cable tv-36. it provides an anonymous medium through which mit' b' students can say those things they might otherwise find' b" difficult, inconvenient or impossible to say in person. it's" b' also a way to send fun or totally random messages to your' b' friends over the air. it is similar to the anonymous message' b" pages found in many college newspapers, except that it's" b" electronic in nature and it's free." b'' b'messages can be posted to the service via email. for more' b'' b'' b'miscellaneous' b'=============' b'' b'_____' b"<5.1 what is ``digital cash''?" b'' b'with digital encryption and authentication technologies, the' b'possibility of a widespread digital cash system may someday be' b'realized. a system utilizing codes sent between users and banks' b"(similar to today's checking system except entirely digital) may" b'be one approach. the issues of cryptography, privacy, and' b'anonymity are closely associated with transfer of cash in an' b'economy. see the article in scientific american by david chaum' b'(~dec.1992).' b'' b'an experimental digital bank is run by karl barrus' b'cypherpunks mailing list. to use the server send mail to' b'' b'::' b'command: help' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'_____' b"<5.2 what is a ``hacker'' or ``cracker''?" b'' b'these terms arouse strong feelings by many on their meaning,' b'especially on the internet. in the general news media in the past' b'a person who uses computers and networks to malicious ends (such as' b'breaking into systems) has been referred to as a hacker, but most' b"internet users prefer the term ``cracker'' for this. instead, a" b"``hacker'' is perceived as a benign but intensely ambitious," b'curious, and driven computer user who explores obscure areas of a' b'system, for example---something of a proud electronic pioneer and' b'patriot. this is the sense intended in this document. see also' b"the ``hacker's dictionary'' and the faq `alt-security-faq'." b'' b'' b'_____' b"<5.3 what is a ``cypherpunk''?" b'' b'from the charter of the cypherpunk mailing list:' b'' b' cypherpunks assume privacy is a good thing and wish there were' b' more of it. cypherpunks acknowledge that those who want privacy' b' must create it for themselves and not expect governments,' b' corporations, or other large, faceless organizations to grant' b' them privacy out of beneficence. cypherpunks know that people' b' have been creating their own privacy for centuries with whispers,' b' envelopes, closed doors, and couriers. cypherpunks do not seek' b' to prevent other people from speaking about their experiences or' b' their opinions.' b'' b'see information on the cypherpunk mailing list below.' b'' b'see also the cryptoanarchist manifesto and the cryptography glossary' b'in soda.berkeley.edu:/pub/cypherpunks.' b'' b'_____' b"<5.4 what is `steganography' and anonymous pools?" b'' b"closely associated with encryption is `steganography' or the" b'techniques for not only pursuing private (encrypted) communication' b'but concealing the very existence of the communication itself.' b'many new possibilities in this area are introduced with the' b'proliferation of computer technology. for example, it is possible' b'to encode messages in the least-significant bits of images,' b"typically the most 'noisy'. in addition, when such an item is" b'posted in a public place (such as a newsgroup), virtually' b'untraceable communication can take place between sender and' b'receiver. for steganographic communications in the electronic' b'realm one another possibility is setting up a mailing list where' b'individual messages get broadcast to the entire list and individual' b'users decode particular messages with their unique key. an' b'anonymous pool has been set up by miron cuperman' b'commands in the subject line:' b'' b'subscribe' b'unsubscribe' b'help' b'' b'_____' b"<5.5 what is `security through obscurity'?" b'' b"`security through obscurity' refers to the attempt to gain" b'protection from system weaknesses by hiding sensitive information' b'or programs relating to them. for example, a company may not make' b"public information on its software's encryption techniques to evade" b"`attacks' based on knowledge of it. another example would be" b'concealing data on the existence of security holes or bugs in' b'operating systems. or, some reliance may be made on the fact that' b'some standard or mechanism with potential problems is serious' b"because they are ``not widely known'' or ``not widely used.'' this" b'argument is occasionally applied to mechanisms for email and usenet' b"posting `forgery'. `security through obscurity' is regarded as a" b'very feeble technique at best and inappropriate and ineffective at' b"worst (also called the ``head-in-the-sand approach''). see the faq" b'for alt.security.' b'' b'some remarks of john perry barlow, cofounder of the electronic' b'frontier foundation, directed to nsa agents at the first' b'international symposium on national security national' b'competitiveness held in mclean, virginia dec. b'' b' digitized information is very hard to stamp classified or keep' b" contained. this stuff is incredibly leaky and volatile. it's" b' almost a life form in its ability to self-propagate. if' b" something hits the net and it's something which people on there" b' find interesting it will spread like a virus of the mind. i' b' believe you must simply accept the idea that we are moving into' b' an environment where any information which is at all interesting' b' to people is going to get out. and there will be very little' b' that you can do about it. this is not a bad thing in my view,' b' but you may differ...' b'' b'_____' b"<5.6 what are `identity daemons'?" b'' b'rfc-931 describes a protocol standard that allows unix programs to' b"query a remote user's login name after connection to a local" b'communication socket (a connection of this type is established' b'during ftp and telnet sessions, for example). the standard is not' b'widely supported, perhaps of internet sites currently implement' b'it but the number is increasing. the mechanism is detrimental to' b'anonymity. regular users cannot disable it but system' b'adminstrators can circumvent it. this standard may represent a' b'trend toward greater authentication mechanisms.' b'' b'_____' b'<5.7 what new standards are needed to guard electronic privacy?' b'' b'' b'remailing/posting' b'-----------------' b'' b'- stable, secure, protected, officially sanctioned and permitted,' b'publicly and privately operated anonymous servers and hubs.' b'- official standards for encryption and anonymity in mail and usenet' b'postings.' b'- truly anonymous protocols with source and destination information' b'obscured or absent and hidden routing mechanisms (chaining,' b'encrypted addresses, etc.)' b'- standards for anonymous email addressing, embedding files, and' b'remailer site chaining.' b'' b'general' b'-------' b'' b'- recognition of anonymity, cryptography, and related privacy' b'shields as legitimate, useful, desirable, and crucial by the' b'general public and their governments.' b'- widespread use and implementation of these technologies' b'by systems designers into' b"hardware, software, and standards, implemented `securely,'" b"`seamlessly,' and `transparently'." b'- general shift of use, dependence, and reliance to means other than' b'wiretapping and electronic surveillance by law enforcement' b'agencies.' b'- publicity, retraction, and dissolution of laws and government' b'agencies opposed to privacy, replaced by structures dedicated to' b'strengthening and protecting it.' b'' b'' b'issues' b'======' b'' b'_____' b'<6.1 what is the electronic frontier foundation (eff)?' b'' b'from ftp.eff.org:/pub/eff/mission_statement:' b'' b' a new world is arising in the vast web of digital, electronic' b' media which connect us. computer-based communication media like' b' electronic mail and computer conferencing are becoming the basis' b' of new forms of community. these communities without a single,' b' fixed geographical location comprise the first settlements on an' b' electronic frontier.' b'' b' while well-established legal principles and cultural norms give' b' structure and coherence to uses of conventional media like' b' newspapers, books, and telephones, the new digital media do not' b' so easily fit into existing frameworks. conflicts come about as' b' the law struggles to define its application in a context where' b' fundamental notions of speech, property, and place take' b' profoundly new forms. people sense both the promise and the' b' threat inherent in new computer and communications technologies,' b' even as they struggle to master or simply cope with them in the' b' workplace and the home.' b'' b' the electronic frontier foundation has been established to help' b' civilize the electronic frontier; to make it truly useful and' b' beneficial not just to a technical elite, but to everyone; and to' b" do this in a way which is in keeping with our society's highest" b' traditions of the free and open flow of information and' b' communication.' b'' b'eff was started by the multimillionaire mitchell kapor, founder of' b'lotus software, and john barlow, lyricist for the grateful dead' b'rock band. a highly publicized endeavor of the organization' b'involved the legal defense of steve jackson games after an fbi' b'raid and an accompanying civil suit (see section on ``steve' b"jackson games''). the foundation publishes eff news (effector" b'' b'in a letter to mitchell kapor from the chairman of the subcommittee' b'with primary jurisdiction over telecommunications policy dated' b'november representative edward j. markey complemented' b'mitchell kapor on his ``insights on the development of a national' b"public information infrastructure'' which ``were appreciated greatly" b"by myself and the members of the subcommittee'' (complete text in" b'ftp.eff.com:/pub/pub-infra/1991-12):' b'' b' ...we need to pursue policies that encourage the bell companies to' b' work with other sectors of the communications industry to create' b' a consumer-oriented, public information network. please let me or' b' my staff know what policies you and others in the computer' b' industry believe would best serve the public interest in creating' b' a reasonably priced, widely available network in which' b' competition is open and innovation rewarded. i also want to' b' learn what lessons from the computer industry over the past ten' b' to fifteen years should apply to the current debate on' b' structuring the information and communications networks of the' b' future....i ask your help in gaining input from the computer' b' industry so that the subcommittee can shape policies that will' b' bring this spirit of innovation and entrepreneurship to the' b' information services industry.' b'' b'ftp.eff.org' b'===========' b'' b'/pub/eff/about-eff' b'---' b'a file of basic information about eff including goals, mission,' b'achievements, and current projects. contains a membership form.' b'' b'/pub/eff/mission-statement' b'---' b'eff mission statement.' b'' b'/pub/eff/historical/founding-announcement' b'---' b'eff founding press release.' b'' b'/pub/eff/historical/eff-history' b'---' b"john perry barlow's ``not terribly brief history of the eff'' (july" b'10, how eff was conceived and founded, major legal cases,' b'and the organizational directions.' b'' b'/pub/eff/historical/legal-case-summary' b'---' b'eff legal case summary.' b'' b'' b'_____' b'<6.2 who are computer professionals for social responsibility (cpsr)?' b'' b'the computer professionals for social responsibility have been' b'working to protect and promote electronic civil liberties issues' b'since the group has three offices (palo alto, cambridge,' b'washington, dc) and chapters. it is involved in litigation' b'against the fbi, the nsa, nist, the secret service and other other' b'u.s. government agencies to declassify and provide documentation' b'on issues s