tutional' b' warrant, agents of the secret service conducted a search of the' b' sjg office. when they left they took a manuscript being prepared' b' for publication, private electronic mail, and several computers,' b' including the hardware and software of the sjg computer bulletin' b' board system. yet jackson and his business were not only' b' innocent of any crime, but never suspects in the first place.' b' the raid had been staged on the unfounded suspicion that' b" somewhere in jackson's office there `might be' a document" b' compromising the security of the telephone system.' b'' b'fbi agents involved in the seizure were named in a civil suit filed' b'on behalf of steve jackson games by the electronic frontier' b'foundation. see information on eff below. from an article by joe' b'abernathy in the houston chronicle ~feb b'' b' austin an electronic civil rights case against the secret' b' service closed thursday with a clear statement by federal' b' district judge sam sparks that the service failed to conduct a' b' proper investigation in a notorious computer crime crackdown,' b' and went too far in retaining custody of seized equipment.' b'' b' secret service special agent timothy foley of chicago, who was in' b' charge of three austin computer search-and-seizures on march b" that led to the lawsuit, stoically endured spark's rebuke" b" over the service's poor investigation and abusive computer" b' seizure policies. while the service has seized dozens of' b' computers since the crackdown began in this is the first' b' case to challenge the practice.' b'' b' sparks grew visibly angry when it was established that the austin' b' science fiction magazine and game book publisher was never' b' suspected of a crime, and that agents did not do even marginal' b' research to establish a criminal connection between the firm and' b' the suspected illegal activities of an employee, or to determine' b' that the company was a publisher. indeed, agents testified that' b' they were not even trained in the privacy protection act at the' b' special secret service school on computer crime.' b'' b' "how long would it have taken you, mr. foley, to find out what' b' steve jackson games did, what it was?" asked sparks. "an hour?' b'' b' "was there any reason why, on march you could not return to' b' steve jackson games a copy, in floppy disk form, of everything' b' taken?' b'' b' "did you read the article in business week magazine where it had' b' a picture of steve jackson a law-abiding, tax-paying citizen' b' saying he was a computer crime suspect?' b'' b' "did it ever occur to you, mr. foley, that seizing this material' b' could harm steve jackson economically?"' b'' b' foley replied, "no, sir," but the judge offered his own answer.' b'' b' "you actually did, you just had no idea anybody would actually go' b' out and hire a lawyer and sue you."' b'' b' more than has been spent by the electronic frontier' b' foundation in bringing the case to trial. the eff was founded by' b' mitchell kapor amid a civil liberties movement sparked in large' b' part by the secret service computer crime crackdown.' b'' b'' b'ftp.eff.org' b'===========' b'' b'/pub/cud/papers/sundevil' b'---' b'a collection of information on operation sundevil by the epic' b'nonprofit publishing project. everything you wanted to know but' b'could never find.' b'' b'/pub/cud/papers/sj-resp' b'---' b"steve jackson's response to the charges against him." b'' b'_____' b'<6.4 what is integrated services digital network (isdn)?' b'' b'isdn is a high-speed data communications standard that utilizes' b'existing copper telephone lines, and is a possible inexpensive and' b'intermediate alternative to laying fiber optic cable for phone' b'networks. the speeds involved may be sufficient for audio and' b'video transmission applications. g. v. der leun in the file' b'ftp.eff.org: /pub/pub-infra/1991-11:' b'' b' telecommunications in the united states is at a crossroads. with' b' the regional be