tions" b' service providers and hardware manufacturers to make their' b" systems 'tappable' by providing 'back doors' through which law" b' enforcement officers could intercept communications. furthermore,' b' this capability would have been provided undetectably, while the' b' communications was in progress, exclusive of any communications' b' between other parties, regardless of the mobility of the target' b" of the fbi's investigation, and without degradation of service." b'' b' ...under the proposal, the department of justice (doj) can keep' b' communications products off the market if it determines that' b" these products do not meet the doj's own guidelines. this" b' [could] result in increased costs and reduced competitiveness for' b' service providers and equipment manufacturers, since they will be' b' unlikely to add any features that may result in a doj rejection' b' of their entire product. ...the fbi proposal suggests that the' b" cost of this wiretapping 'service' to the bureau would have to be" b' borne by the service provider itself...' b'' b' the electronic frontier foundation organized a broad coalition of' b' public interest and industry groups, from computer professionals' b' for social responsibilty (cpsr) and the aclu to at&t and sun' b' microsystems, to oppose the legislation. a white paper produced' b' by the eff and ratified by the coalition, entitled, `an analysis' b" of the fbi digital telephony proposal,' was widely distributed" b' throughout the congress. the justice department lobbied hard' b' in the final days to get congress to take up the bill before' b' congress adjourned, but the bill never found a congressional' b' sponsor (and was therefore never officially introduced). the fbi' b' [may] reintroduce "digital telephony" when the 103rd congress' b' convenes in january.' b'' b'ftp.eff.org' b'===========' b'' b'/pub/eff/legislation/fbi-wiretap-bill' b'/pub/eff/legislation/new-fbi-wiretap-bill' b'---' b'a bill to ensure the continuing 